<h2>Event in December 2019</h2>
<br><br>
In the pre-Christmas period of 2019, a far southward reaching trough of cold polar air ensured that the polar front and the polar jet above it extended far to the south. Due to the strong temperature gradient between this cold air and the warm maritime subtropical air, strong baroclinicity was generated below the jet stream.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/dec2019/2019-12-20T00-00Z_Eumetrain_Mapviewer_2.jpg"><img alt="" src="../images/dec2019/2019-12-20T00-00Z_Eumetrain_Mapviewer_2.jpg" width="500px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 1: Synoptic situation at 20 December 2019 00 UTC, OPERA weather radar data and analysed surface pressure [hPa] from the ECMWF model.</em>
<br><br>
<br><br>
This flow regime ensured that within a short period of time, several rapidly moving low-pressure systems could travel across Western and Central Europe. Low-pressure system Yadid caused hurricane gusts over the British Isles on 18 December and then moved over Iceland to take on the role of the steering central depression. On 19 and 20 December, the low-pressure system Zelio moved along the Atlantic coast of northern Spain and France. Heavy rain was reported in parts of South East England which resulted in flooded roads. In addition to hurricane-like gusts over the Iberian Peninsula and the coastal region of France, there were also strong foehn winds over the Alps. This caused temperatures above 15&deg;C and stormy winds on the northern side of the Alps.
<br><br>
Subsequently low-pressure area Zelio moved north and took over the role of the steering Icelandic depression. South of it, low-pressure system Ailton rushed towards the northern French Atlantic coast. In the evening of 21 December, the depression split up. While Ailton I moved across the English Channel, Ailton II moved over the northwestern Mediterranean. During this time, stormy winds with hurricane gusts occurred over the Madeira Islands, Corsica and Sardinia. Further heavy rainfall was observed in France which is depicted in Figure 1.
<br><br>
<h2>Specific climate indicators for December 2019</h2>
<br><br>
Temperatures in December 2019 were above the 1981-2010 average throughout Europe. It was especially warm in the east. For the Moscow area record-breaking mild temperatures and absence of snow occured. Northern Finland also experienced unusually mild temperatures. Statistics for Sodankyl&auml; show an anomaly relative to 1981-2010 of 6.2&deg;C for December 2019. Since 1961, December anomalies have ranged from -9.5&deg;C to 8.5&deg;C at this observatory. Exceptionally high anomalies in minimum temperatures occurred over the northeastern Europe and neighbouring Russia with values up to 10&deg;C.
